The following assumptions were made regarding the financial plan:
&nbsp;
* Predicted sales of \$29,210
&nbsp;
* Dividend amounting to \$2,100
&nbsp;
* Predicted increase in the balance sheet (assets) accounts proportional to sales

Now, let us compute the percentage of cost in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Cost}&=\frac{\text{Cost}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$17,300}{\$25,400}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.68}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{68\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of cost in proportion to the sales is 68\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected cost:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Cost}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$29,210}\times{68\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$19,862.80}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected cost is \$19,862.80.**

Now, let us compute the projected taxable income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Taxable Income}&=\text{Projected Sales}-\text{Projected Cost}\\[12pt]
&={\$29,210}-{\$19,862.80}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$9,347.20}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Taxable income is \$9,347.20.**

Now, let us compute the taxes:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Taxes}&=\text{Taxable income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$9,347.20}\times{21\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$1,962.91}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected taxes is \$1,962.91.**

Now, let us compute the projected net income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Net Income}&=\text{Taxable Income}-\text{Taxes}\\[12pt]
&={\$9,347.20}-{\$1,962.91}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$7,384.29}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected net income is \$7,384.29.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of assets in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Asset}&=\frac{\text{Asset}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$61,000}{\$25,400}\times100\\[12pt]
&={2.40}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{240\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of asset in proportion to the sales is 240\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Assets}&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$29,210}\times{240\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$70,104}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected assets is \$70,104.**

Now, let us compute the dividend payout ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Dividend Payout Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Dividend}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$2,100}{\$6,399}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.33}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{33\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The dividend payout ratio is 33\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected dividend:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Dividend}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$7,384.29}\times{33\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$2,436.82}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected dividend is \$2,436.82.**

Now, let us compute the retained earnings:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retained Earnings}&=\text{Net Income}-\text{Dividend}\\[12pt]
&={\$6,399}-{\$2,100}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$4,299}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retained earnings is \$4,299.**

Now, let us compute the retention ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Retained Earnings}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$4,299}{\$6,399}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.67}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{67\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retention ratio is 67\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected retained earnings:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Retained Earnings}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$7,384.29}\times{67\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$4,947.47}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected retained earnings is \$4,947.47.**

Now, let us compute the total equity:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Equity}&=\text{Equity}+\text{Dividend}+\text{Retained Earnings}\\[12pt]
&={\$34,100}+{\$2,436.82}+{\$4,947.47}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$41,484.29}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total equity amounts to \$41,484.29.**

Now, let us compute the total debt and equity:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Debt and Equity}&=\text{Debt}+\text{Equity}\\[12pt]
&={\$26,900}+{\$41,484.29}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$68,384.29}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total debt and equity amounts to \$68,384.29.**

To balance the total debt and equity and the total assets, we are to compute the external financing needed by the company:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{EFN}&=\text{Total Assets}-\text{Total Debt and Equity}\\[12pt]
&={\$70,104}-{\$68,384.29}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$1,719.71}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The external financing needed amounts to \$1,719.71.**

### Next, let us provide the given income statement.

$$
\begin{array}{c}
\textbf{Cardinal, Inc.}\\
\text{Income Statement}
\end{array}
$$

$$
\begin{array}{lr}
\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}\\[10pt]
\text{Sales}&\$25,400.00\\
\text{Cost of Sales}&\underline{17,300.00}\\
\text{Taxable Income}&8,100.00\\
\text{Taxes(21\%)}&\underline{1,701.00}\\
\textbf{Net Income}&\underline{\underline{\$6,399.00}}

\end{array}
$$

### Last, provide the given balance sheet.

$$
\begin{array}{c}
\textbf{Cardinal, Inc.}\\
\text{Balance Sheet}
\end{array}
$$

$$
\begin{array}{lrlr}
\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}&\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}\\[10pt]
\text{Assets}&\$61,000.00&\text{Liabilities}&\$26,900.00\\
&\underline{\text{-----------}}&\text{Equity}&\underline{34,100.00}\\
\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$61,000.00}}&\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$61,000.00}}
\end{array}
$$

### Compute the percentage share of the cost of sales from the sales.

Computation of the percentage share of the cost of sales is needed to compute the projected cost of sales.

The formula is as follows.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Cost of Sales from Sales}& = \dfrac{\text{Cost of Sales}}{\text{Sales}}


\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the computation of the percentage of the cost of sales from the sales is as follows.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Cost of Sales from Sales}& = \dfrac{\$17,300.00}{\$25,400.00}\\[15pt]
&= 0.6811 \times 100\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{68.11\%}}


\end{aligned}
$$

The percentage of the cost of sales from the sales is **68.11%**.

### Compute the projected cost of sales.

Using the calculated percentage of the cost of sales, we will use this percentage share to compute the projected cost of sales.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Cost of Sales}&= \text{Projected Sales} \times \text{Percentage of COS}


\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected cost of sales is calculated as follows.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Cost of Sales}&= \$29,210.00 \times 68.11\%\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\textbf{\$19,894.93}}

\end{aligned}
$$

The projected cost of sales is **$19,894.93**.

### Compute the business tax.

The business tax is treated as operating cost, which is deducted from the taxable income to compute the net income.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Business Tax}&= \$9,315.07 \times 21\%\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\textbf{\$1,956.16}}

\end{aligned}
$$

The projected business tax is **$1,956.16**.

### Compute the projected dividend.

The projected dividend is calculated by multiplying the net income with the payout ratio. Based on the problem, the company wishes to maintain a payout ratio.

The formula is as follows.
$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Payout Ratio}& = \dfrac{\text{Declared Dividends}}{\text{Net Income}}


\end{aligned}
$$

### Calculate the payout ratio.

The payout ratio will be used in calculating the projected dividend.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Payout Ratio}& = \dfrac{\$2,100.00}{\$6,399.00}\\[15pt]
&= .3282 \times 100\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{32.82\%}}


\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the payout ratio is 32.82%

### After computing the payout ratio, we can now calculate the projected dividend.

The projected dividend is calculated by multiplying the payout ratio with the projected net income.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Dividend}&= \text{Payout Ratio} \times \text{Projected Net Income}\\[15pt]
&= 32.82\%  \times \$7,358.91\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$2,415.19}}

\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected dividend is **$2,415.19**.

### Compute the percentage of increase in sales.

The percentage of increase in sales will be used to calculate the company's projected assets.

The formula is as follows.
$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Increase in Sales}& = \dfrac{\text{Projected Sales}}{\text{Current Sales}}


\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the percentage of increase in sales is calculated as follows.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Increase in Sales}& = \dfrac{\$29,210.00}{\$25,400.00}\\[15pt]
&=1.15  \times 100\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{115}\%}

\end{aligned}
$$

The percentage increase in sales is **$115%** or the sales increased by **15%**.

### Prepare the Pro Forma balance sheet

$$
\begin{array}{c}
\textbf{Cardinal, Inc.}\\
\textbf{Pro Forma}\\
\text{Balance Sheet}
\end{array}
$$

$$
\begin{array}{lrlr}
\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}&\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}\\[10pt]
\text{Assets}&\$70,150.00&\text{Liabilities}&\$26,900.00\\
&\underline{\text{-----------}}&\text{Equity}&\underline{39,043.72}\\
\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$70,150.00}}&\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$65,943.72}}\\[5pt]
&&\textbf{EFN}&\underline{\text{\$4,206.28}}\\
&&\textbf{Total}&\underline{\underline{\$70,150.00}}
\end{array}
$$

Therefore, the new total of the balance sheet is **$70,150.00**.
